Issues.Body:
Im add custom colors to use in my rails app this is the following code: 

app/assets/stylesheets/new_colors.css.scss

```
@import "bulma";

$pink: hsl(319,100%,85%);
$pink-invert: findColorInvert($pink);

$light-blue: hsl(180,100%,85%);
$light-blue-invert: findColorInvert($light-blue);

$purple: hsl(262,100%,82%);
$purple-invert: findColorInvert($purple);

$red: hsl(0,100%,84%);
$red-invert: findColorInvert($red);

$custom-colors: (
  "pink": (
    $pink,
    $pink-invert,
  ),
  "light-blue": (
    $light-blue,
    $light-blue-invert,
  ),
  "purple": (
    $purple,
    $purple-invert,
  ),
  "red": (
    $red,
    $red-invert,
  ),
);

$colors: map-merge($colors, $custom-colors);

@import "bulma";
```

app/assets/stylesheets/appliclation.css.scss

```
@import "bulma";
@import "new_colors"
```
when use this on letters helpers work perfectly, but in buttons colors helpers dont work

This is about **Bulma**.

### Overview of the problem

This is about the Bulma **CSS framework**
I'm using Bulma **version** [0.9.2].

### Description

When image used in Card and on image is "is-rounded" helper, then image is not rounded on top borders.

### Steps to Reproduce

```html
<div class="card">
	<div class="card-image" style="position:relative; margin-bottom: 1.5rem">
		<div class="image is-96x96">
			<img class="is-rounded lazyload" style="border: 5px solid white;" alt="10Geek" src="URL">
		</div>
	</div>
</div>
```
### Expected behavior

Image will be rounded like in previous Bulma versions

### Actual behavior

Image is not rounded.

CSS applied:
```css
.card-image:last-child img {
    border-bottom-left-radius: 0.25rem;
    border-bottom-right-radius: 0.25rem;
}
.card-image:first-child img {
    border-top-left-radius: 0.25rem;
    border-top-right-radius: 0.25rem;
}
```
CSS for is-rounded image is not applied:
```css
.image img.is-rounded {
    border-radius: 290486px;
}
```
Sollution?
**A.**
```css
.image img.is-rounded {
    border-radius: 290486px !important;
}
```
**B**
```css
.card-image:last-child img:not(.is-rounded) {
    border-bottom-left-radius: 0.25rem;
    border-bottom-right-radius: 0.25rem;
}
.card-image:first-child img:not(.is-rounded) {
    border-top-left-radius: 0.25rem;
    border-top-right-radius: 0.25rem;
}
```
**C**
```css
.card-image:last-child img.is-rounded {
    border-bottom-left-radius: 290486px;
    border-bottom-right-radius: 290486px;
}
.card-image:first-child img.is-rounded {
    border-top-left-radius: 290486px;
    border-top-right-radius: 290486px;
}
```

Each of possible possultions have pros & cons. But I think that 290486px is in Sass variable $radius-rounded, than solution **C** will be the best.

Since margins can also contain minus values, appropriate modifiers would be useful to have.

```css
.m--1 { margin:-.25rem }
.m--2 { margin:-.5rem }
```
